   242	Because this position seems to arouse fierce controversy, let me stress
   243	our motivation: if quantum theory were not successful pragmatically, we
   244	would have no interest in its interpretation. It is precisely because of
   245	the enormous success of the QM mathematical formalism that it becomes
   246	crucially important to learn what that mathematics means. To find a
   247	rational physical interpretation of the QM formalism ought to be
   248	considered the top priority research problem of theoretical physics;
   249	until this is accomplished, all other theoretical results can only be
   250	provisional and temporary.
   251	
   252	This conviction has affected the whole course of my career. I had
   253	intended originally to specialize in Quantum Electrodynamics working
   254	with J. R. Oppenheimer; but this proved to be impossible. Whenever I
   255	look at any quantum-mechanical calculation, the basic craziness of what
   256	we are doing rises in my gorge and I have to stop and try to find some
   257	different way of looking at the problem, that makes physical sense.
   258	Gradually I came to see that the resolution cannot be found within the
   259	confines of the traditional thinking of physicists; the foundations of
